Linear models

I chose age, attitude and deep as explanatory variables and fitted the linear model where points is the target variable.

model1 <- lm(points ~ age + attitude + deep, data = students2014)
summary(model1)
##

## Residual standard error: 5.307 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2043, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1896 
## F-statistic: 13.87 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 4.305e-08

From the summary we can see the model1 parameters. Estimates tell the relationships between the explanatory variables and the target variable. By using the estimates we can also write down the linear equation: points=15.60773-0.07716age+3.59413attitude-0.60275deep.Then there are also standard errors in the summary, and t-values from the statistical test that was performed and p-values which tell if the explanatory variable is statistically significant variable. Usually we choose the level of significance, often it is 0,05. If we look at the variable age, we see that the p-value is 0,149 > 0,05, so age is not statistically significant variable. Variable deep is not either statistically significant variable because its p-value is even higher 0,423 > 0,05. But if we look at the variable attitude, p-value is very small 2.56e-09 < 0,05, which means that it is statistically significant.

Next I remove age and deep from the model, because they were not statistically significant.

model2 <- lm(points ~  attitude, data = students2014)
summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = students2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

From the summary we can see now the model2 parameters which have now changed a bit because of the removal of those other variables. If we look at the relationship between the variables points and attitude, the attitude is statistically significant variable, p-value is very small 4.12e-09 < 0,05. Model equation is: points=11.6372+3.5255attitude. This means that when attitude increases by one, exam points will increase 3.5255 points on average.

Multiple R-squared is: 0.1906.This means that the fitted model explains 19,06 % of the variation in exam points. In my opinion, R squared is quite low (R squared is always between 0 and 100 %), but on the other hand we have statistically significant variable, which is good.

Diagnostic plots

Diagnostic plots can tell us about the goodness of the fitted model. There are few assumptions related to the evaluation of fitted models. Often when analyzing fitted models we look at residuals and errors. Errors are assumed to be normally distributed and they are not correlated. They are assumed to have constant variance and the size of a error should not be dependent on the explanatory variables. These assumptions we can evaluate with a QQ-plot, a scatter plot of residuals versus model predictions and with a residuals vs leverage plot.

plot(model2, which = c(1)) # Residuals vs fitted plot of model2

Residuals vs fitted plot can tell us about the constant variance of errors which is assumed. If we look at the residuals vs fitted plot, we can see that residuals are quite well distributed around the 0-line, which means that the variance of errors is constant. There are only three points which might be outliers (145, 56, 35).

plot(model2, which = c(2)) # QQ-plot of model2

QQ-plot can help us figure out if the assumption of normality of the errors is true. If we look at the QQ-plot we can see that points follow the line quite nicely, so we can assume that the errors are normally distributed.

plot(model2, which = c(5)) # Residuals vs Leverage plot of model2

Leverage of observations can tell us if a single observation has a high impact on the model. If we look at the Residuals vs Leverage plot we see that the leverage scale is from 0 to 0,04, so their values are small and there aren´t any outliers. So the leverage seem regular, which also means that the errors are regular.

Based on the results of the model validity tests I would say that the model that was fitted is okay.

I chose 4 different variables: sex, grades, absences and freetime. My hypotheses are:

  1. Male sex has higher alcohol consumption compared to females.
  2. Lower grades at school result in greater alcohol consumption.
  3. More absences at school can be explained by higher alcohol consumption.
  4. More freetime can lead to higher alcohol consumption.

Logistic regression

I will use logistic regression to statistically explore the relationship between my chosen variables: sex, grades, absences and freetime and the binary high/low alcohol consumption variable as the target variable.

m1 <- glm(high_use ~ G3 + absences + sex + freetime, data = alc_consump, family = "binomial")
summary(m1)

If we now look at the summary of the fitted model, we can see the model estimates and parameters and also the p-values of the statistical test (Pr(>|z|)). If we look at the p-values, all of them are smaller that 0,05, so all of the chosen variables are statistically significant. If we compare the p-values, grades (G3) has the highest value 0,0393 which is quite close to 0,05. So with grades the significance is not so great as for example in the case of absences. The p-value for absences is very small 5.12e-05, which means that there is statistically significant relationship between absences and high alcohol consumption. In the summary sexM, means that when comparing females to males, male sex has statistically significant relationship between high alcohol consumption, p-value 0,00022. However, there are statistically significant relationships between all the chosen variables and high alcohol consumption.

Next I will present the coefficients of the model as odds ratios, including confidence intervals

OR <- coef(m1) %>% exp #computing odds ratios
CI <- confint(m1) %>% exp #computing confidence intervals
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
cbind(OR, CI) #printing out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
##                    OR      2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.1462213 0.04110958 0.4958846
## G3          0.9264847 0.86089482 0.9960244
## absences    1.0986708 1.05199101 1.1525937
## sexM        2.5329476 1.55515113 4.1769987
## freetime    1.3558665 1.05718812 1.7513727

Now we can see ORs. We also need the original coefficients of the model for explaining the results.

coef(m1)
## (Intercept)          G3    absences        sexM    freetime 
## -1.92263391 -0.07635776  0.09410107  0.92938367  0.30444073

Grades (G3):OR is 0,93, but the coefficient is negative -0,076, which means that when grades grow bigger the probability of high alcohol consumption decreases 0,93 fold. If we look at the CI [0.86, 0.996], we can see that the upper limit is basically 1, which means that there is no clear evidence of an association between grades and high alcohol consumption.

absences: OR is 1,10, and the coefficient is positive 0,094, which means that when absences increase by one, the probability of high alcohol consumption increases 1,10 fold.

sexM: OR is 2,53 and the coefficient is positive 0,93, which means that when we compare females to males, being male increases the probability of high alcohol consumption 2,53 fold. SexM has also the widest CI [1.55, 4.17].

freetime: OR is 1.36 and the coefficient is positive 0,30, which means that when freetime increases, the probability of high alcohol consumption increases 1,36 fold.

Based on these results, my hypotheses were almost right. Only the variable grades were shown not to have statistically significant relationship with high alcohol use.

Calculating the mean predictive error and average number of wrong predictions to see how well predictions are made

loss_func <- function(class, prob) { # defining a loss function (mean prediction error)
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc_consump$high_use, prob = 0) # calling loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the data
## [1] 0.3

Based on these model prediction results, I would say that the predictive power of the fitted model is not perfect, because there are differences between the predicted and real results. The average number of wrong predictions is 0.3 (30%). If we compare the performance of the model with performance achieved by some simple guessing strategy, I think it is better to use statistical methods instead of just guessing. Statistical tests can reveal things that you cannot see by just making a guess or drawing a simple plot.

I will draw the LDA (bi)plot, but first we need the function for lda biplot arrows.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime) # target classes as numeric
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)# plotting the lda results
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2) #adding the arrows

If we look at the model summary and plot, we see that LD1 explains 95 % of the variation in the plot. There is clear cluster in the right side (blue). Rad seems to be significant variable for that. Other colours are not that well separated on the left.

From the plots above, we can see the clustering in different colours. Some clusters are very clearly separated, but in other cases clusters are on top of each other. So I am not quite sure what would be the most optimal number of clusters in this case.

If we compare non-standardized and standardized PCA-plots, they look totally different. Now there are multiple arrows pointing at different directions. PC1 explains 53.6 % of the variance and PC2 16.2 %. Small angle between arrows means high positive correlation, so there is high positive correlation between variables Maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor) and Adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth) which was seen also earlier in the correlation plot. They have also small angle between PC1 which means also high positive correlation between them and they are contributing that dimension. There are multiple arrows pointing at the opposite direction from (Mat.Mor) and (Ado.Birth). They are also affecting PC1 and correlating with it. There are also very small angles between all of them so they are correlating with each other. Those variables are: Expected years of schooling (Edu.exp), Proportion of females versus males with at least secondary education (Edu2.FM), Life expectancy at birth (Life.Exp) and Gross National Income per capita (GNI). GNI arrow is still pointing in the same direction as in the non-standardized PCA-plot. There are still two variables Proportion of females versus males in the labour force (Labo.FM) and Percetange of female representatives in parliament (Parli.F) which are pointing upwards, in the same direction as PC2 so they are correlating with it. There is clear angle between them, so the correlation between those variables is smaller but still existing. But angles between the arrows pointing up versus others pointing horizontally are quite big, which means that there is no correlation between them. Almost all the lenghts of the arrows are equal, which means that the standard deviations are quite equal.

I think the first two PC dimensions explain well the distributions of different countries based on different variables. If we look at the standardized human data PCA plot, we can see that in the right side, there are a lot of African countries, whereas on the left side there are Westerns countries and the Nordic countries in the left upper corner. And also in the bottom of the plot are mainly Arabic countries. We all know that there are differences between those countries which are also shown in this plot. For example in the African countries Maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor) and Adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth) are higher, in the Western countries Expected years of schooling (Edu.exp), Proportion of females versus males with at least secondary education (Edu2.FM), Life expectancy at birth (Life.Exp) and Gross National Income per capita (GNI) are higher and also in the Nordic countries the Percentage of female representatives in parliament (Parli.F) is higher as we know from Finland for example. Whereas in some of the Arabic countries the situation is opposite considering the Percentage of female representatives in parliament. But there are also exceptions like Rwanda in the up.

Here are some thoughts about the relationships between variables in tea data based on MCA factor map. Distances between variables in MCA plot tells about the similarity of the variables, closer they are to each other more similar they are. For example females (F) and males (M) are quite far away from each other so they are different. +60 and black are close to each other so maybe older people usually drink black tea. Green is also quite close to effect on health so maybe green tea has an effect on health compared to black tea for example. Age groups 35-44 and 45-59 are quite close to each other so maybe they have quite similar habits. Whereas 15-24 are far away from everything. Females (F) are close to +2/day, so maybe they drink tea more often. No sugar is closer to females and older people and sugar is closer to males and younger people so maybe this tells something about who uses sugar in their tea more often.

Even though, we can see the differences between groups quite clearly, we should run some statistical test to be sure.

Now we have more than 2 variables, so we cannot use two sample t-test to see if there are statistically significant differences between groups. I will use function aov from stats package to see if there are differences between groups.

library(stats)
dif <- aov(mean ~ Group, data = RATSS_3)
summary(dif)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)

From the summary we can see that F value of the statistical test is very high 483.6 and p-value is very small (3.39e-12) which mean that there are statistically significant differences between diet groups.

In BPRS data 40 male subjects were randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups and each subject was rated on the brief psychiatric rating scale (BPRS) measured before treatment (week 0) and then weekly for eight weeks period. The BPRS assesses the level of 18 symptom constructs each of which is rated from one (not present) to seven (extremely severe). The scale is used to evaluate patients suspected of having schizophrenia. Now I will look if there are differences between treatments groups.

Then we can compare the models again(BPRSL_ref1 and BPRSL_ref2)

# performing an ANOVA test on the two models
anova(BPRSL_ref2, BPRSL_ref1)
## Data: BPRSL
## Models:

Now we can see from the summary that p-value is 0.075 > 0.05, which means that there is no statistically significant difference between the two models, because there was no interaction between week and treatment.

Let´s draw a plot of BPRS again

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, linetype = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)))+
  ggtitle("Bprs-test points in two treatment groups over the weeks")

Then I can create a vector of fitted values and add it to the BPRSL data

# Create a vector of the fitted values
Fitted <- fitted(BPRSL_ref2)

# Creating a new column fitted to BPRSL
BPRSL <- BPRSL %>%
  mutate(Fitted)

Let´s draw the plot again with fitted values

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = Fitted, linetype = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)))+
  ggtitle("Fitted values of bprs-test points in two treatment groups over the weeks")

If we compare the two pictures, we can see that the original values and fitted values decrease over the weeks but there is no clear difference between two treatments groups. However, there are differences between plots and the model could be better, for example that one outlier in group 2 is not separated in fitted value plot anymore.
